00:13:54.890 --> 00:13:58.630
It's a fully forward renderer,
which means that you've got to

00:13:58.630 --> 00:13:59.490
sort your geometry.

00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:01.230
You've got to do all
the sort of PC

00:14:01.230 --> 00:14:03.540
things, in terms of like--

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:05.960
DAN GALPIN: So in all fairness,
so before coming in

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:07.970
here, I actually put this
through PerfHUD.

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:10.070
And PerfHUD, for those
who don't know, is

00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:11.880
NVIDIA's truly epic--

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:13.226
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, you put it
through PerfHUD, but you

00:14:13.226 --> 00:14:14.680
didn't bring it in here
to show everyone?

00:14:14.680 --> 00:14:15.860
Did you bring enough for
the whole class?

00:14:15.860 --> 00:14:16.400
DAN GALPIN: I-- definitely.

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:18.380
So just to mention, PerfHUD
is NVIDIA's

00:14:18.380 --> 00:14:19.375
awesome performance tool.

00:14:19.375 --> 00:14:21.950
It runs only on NVIDIA chips,
but you can actually go

00:14:21.950 --> 00:14:25.440
through and honestly get an
amazing amount of information

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:27.720
about how your GL screens
are rendering.

00:14:27.720 --> 00:14:29.890
It really is an amazing,
amazing tool.

00:14:29.890 --> 00:14:32.110
And I was able to discern
immediately that this app was

00:14:32.110 --> 00:14:33.010
[? ridge ?] rendering.

00:14:33.010 --> 00:14:35.710
The first thing it puts up on
the screen is the background,

00:14:35.710 --> 00:14:38.520
which you know is a bad sign.

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:39.400
And it does--

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:41.010
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:14:41.010 --> 00:14:42.230
A lot of people don't
realize this.

00:14:42.230 --> 00:14:45.420
I am shocked at how many people
don't realize this.

00:14:45.420 --> 00:14:50.570
There is one basic, basic lesson
that you all must learn

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:53.080
if you want your graphics
to be fast.

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:57.000
And that is, you have a
background and/or skybox, they

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:58.540
get drawn last.

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:04.240
Every single GPU ever will do
better if you draw your skybox

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:05.550
and background last.

00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:05.990
DAN GALPIN: Except for one.

00:15:05.990 --> 00:15:08.150
Except for one.

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:08.960
IAN NI-LEWIS: Dude, what?

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:09.610
Which one?

00:15:09.610 --> 00:15:10.960
DAN GALPIN: The Imagination
Technologies GPUs don't

00:15:10.960 --> 00:15:11.550
fricking care.

00:15:11.550 --> 00:15:13.470
They actually draw just
as well either way.

00:15:13.470 --> 00:15:15.210
IAN NI-LEWIS: OK, I'm sorry.

00:15:15.210 --> 00:15:18.120
Everything will do at least
as well or better.

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:19.760
DAN GALPIN: Ah, there we are.

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:22.210
IAN NI-LEWIS: I can't
believe you, man.

00:15:22.210 --> 00:15:22.800
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, yeah.

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:24.740
So basically--

00:15:24.740 --> 00:15:25.480
IAN NI-LEWIS: Actually, no.

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:28.150
They sort, but they
also Z reject.

00:15:28.150 --> 00:15:30.140
DAN GALPIN: They sort, but
the problem is they sort

00:15:30.140 --> 00:15:31.010
everything.

00:15:31.010 --> 00:15:37.490
And so since it re-sorts it
after you send it to it, it

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:38.820
actually wastes just
as much time.

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:40.610
So you waste more CPU sorting
your geography.

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:43.110
