It's so funny because
I literally--

00:28:57.100 --> 00:28:58.720
DAN GALPIN: I'm glad that they
did change the UI, though.

00:28:58.720 --> 00:29:00.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: So at Microsoft,
we were in a position where we

00:29:00.440 --> 00:29:03.670
often looked at other
people's code.

00:29:03.670 --> 00:29:05.930
I would find samples
that I had written.

00:29:05.930 --> 00:29:08.830
And there were comments saying,
"This is sample code.

00:29:08.830 --> 00:29:12.250
Do not cut and paste this code,"
cut and pasted into

00:29:12.250 --> 00:29:13.250
their code.

00:29:13.250 --> 00:29:17.430
I mean, that is how lazy
some developers are.

00:29:17.430 --> 00:29:18.780
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, so basically,
the answer is--

00:29:18.780 --> 00:29:20.310
first of all, are you saying--

00:29:20.310 --> 00:29:20.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, I'm sorry.

00:29:20.740 --> 00:29:21.730
Did I say "lazy"?

00:29:21.730 --> 00:29:23.162
I meant awesome.

00:29:23.162 --> 00:29:24.110
DAN GALPIN: Awesome!

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:24.930
Wait, put up the awesome.

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:26.960
Come on, we need the awesome.

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:30.645
So then it--

00:29:30.645 --> 00:29:31.980
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh yeah.

00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:32.470
DAN GALPIN: All right.

00:29:32.470 --> 00:29:33.285
So--

00:29:33.285 --> 00:29:36.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: We do kind of need
like a psychedelic Dan

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:39.290
with like the word "awesome"--

00:29:39.290 --> 00:29:39.430
there you go.

00:29:39.430 --> 00:29:42.990
DAN GALPIN: So Frima actually
made one of favorite Android

00:29:42.990 --> 00:29:45.150
games, which is a space
shooter for free.

00:29:45.150 --> 00:29:47.870
And the game was cool, but the
best part about it was the

00:29:47.870 --> 00:29:50.410
epically silly story that they
put together for it.

00:29:50.410 --> 00:29:51.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: That was cool.

00:29:51.450 --> 00:29:53.540
By the way, I just want
to interrupt and--

00:29:53.540 --> 00:29:56.610
do you realize that it took me
like 45 minutes to find those

00:29:56.610 --> 00:29:58.900
damn Mandelbrot coordinates?

00:29:58.900 --> 00:30:00.870
DAN GALPIN: [LAUGH], nice.

00:30:00.870 --> 00:30:02.000
IAN NI-LEWIS: Anyway,
go ahead.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.910
DAN GALPIN: So we appreciate
the time and effort you put

00:30:04.910 --> 00:30:05.590
into this show.

00:30:05.590 --> 00:30:07.430
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's a complete
waste of time, actually.

00:30:07.430 --> 00:30:09.360
DAN GALPIN: It is.

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:10.970
But, you know, you
learn something.

00:30:10.970 --> 00:30:12.580
So this game is a game
in which you

00:30:12.580 --> 00:30:15.950
control a squad of nuns.

00:30:15.950 --> 00:30:18.390
IAN NI-LEWIS: Already
I'm sold.

00:30:18.390 --> 00:30:20.250
DAN GALPIN: So the only thing
about this game is that I find

00:30:20.250 --> 00:30:23.110
that most of the time, I--

00:30:23.110 --> 00:30:24.230
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, that's cool.

00:30:24.230 --> 00:30:25.340
I like that art style.

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:26.650
DAN GALPIN: The art
style is awesome.

00:30:26.650 --> 00:30:27.190
Most of the time--

00:30:27.190 --> 00:30:28.130
IAN NI-LEWIS: And this
is actually--

00:30:28.130 --> 00:30:30.450
I have to admit, this is another
thing that we're

00:30:30.450 --> 00:30:32.890
starting to notice is
that even that pause

00:30:32.890 --> 00:30:35.650
button, that's cool.

00:30:35.650 --> 00:30:37.580
Just a lot a little--
and this is one

00:30:37.580 --> 00:30:38.980
thing that's nice about--

00:30:38.980 --> 00:30:42.730
we were actually in a meeting
earlier, not today, but a

00:30:42.730 --> 00:30:43.490
couple days ago.

00:30:43.490 --> 00:30:45.920
And we were talking about what's
different between doing

00:30:45.920 --> 00:30:47.770
apps and doing games.

00:30:47.770 --> 00:30:51.520
And a big piece of it is
games are so awesome.

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:55.580
On Android, you always get a
completely different set of

00:30:55.580 --> 00:30:57.640
ideas and design things.

00:30:57.640 --> 00:30:58.740
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, it's
like going to--

00:30:58.740 --> 00:30:59.460
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's so cool.

00:30:59.460 --> 00:31:01.070
DAN GALPIN: It's like a
designer's paradise.

00:31:01.070 --> 00:31:04.450
Design whatever you want,
as long as it's awesome.

00:31:04.450 --> 00:31:05.950
IAN NI-LEWIS: And that
was sort of this--

00:31:05.950 --> 00:31:06.245
yeah.

00:31:06.245 --> 00:31:09.750
DAN GALPIN: And my hat is off,
by the way, to Frima's

00:31:09.750 --> 00:31:11.240
designers on this one.

00:31:11.240 --> 00:31:13.010
They did a beautiful job
with the art style.

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:13.890
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah,
it's so pretty.

00:31:13.890 --> 00:31:14.930
What do you call that?

00:31:14.930 --> 00:31:17.660
It's like, I don't know,
"Powerpuff Girls" meets "The

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:20.060
Addams Family." It's like
this bizarre emo

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:21.440
cartoon, and it's great.

00:31:21.440 --> 00:31:22.680
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, these
are seriously emo

00:31:22.680 --> 00:31:24.610
nuns that are in this.

00:31:24.610 --> 00:31:25.300
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's a nun?

00:31:25.300 --> 00:31:25.810
DAN GALPIN: That's a nun.

00:31:25.810 --> 00:31:26.150
Yeah, look at that.

00:31:26.150 --> 00:31:27.710
See the hot nun with
the habit?

00:31:27.710 --> 00:31:28.780
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, man.

00:31:28.780 --> 00:31:29.280
DAN GALPIN: I know.

00:31:29.280 --> 00:31:32.530
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's like they
just invaded my nightmares.

00:31:32.530 --> 00:31:39.530
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, so this is
the burly-ass boss nun here

00:31:39.530 --> 00:31:41.460
who takes things out
with her shotgun.

00:31:41.460 --> 00:31:43.060
IAN NI-LEWIS: So she's
a tank nun?

00:31:43.060 --> 00:31:43.890
DAN GALPIN: She's a tank nun.

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:44.310
IAN NI-LEWIS: Nice.

00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:46.120
DAN GALPIN: You see there's
also different kinds of

00:31:46.120 --> 00:31:46.520
characters.

00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:48.060
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, what's
knife nun doing here?

00:31:48.060 --> 00:31:49.250
DAN GALPIN: Knife nun is--

00:31:49.250 --> 00:31:51.410
IAN NI-LEWIS: Kind of standing
back there, being eye candy?

00:31:51.410 --> 00:31:52.600
What's going on there?

00:31:52.600 --> 00:31:53.380
DAN GALPIN: She actually--

00:31:53.380 --> 00:31:54.840
IAN NI-LEWIS: I think that's
actually a little bit

00:31:54.840 --> 00:31:58.000
offensive to both nuns
and women as a whole.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:31:59.860
DAN GALPIN: What?

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:01.980
IAN NI-LEWIS: Just, you
know, the hot nun.

00:32:01.980 --> 00:32:02.270
DAN GALPIN: Why?

00:32:02.270 --> 00:32:04.150
What's wrong with
nuns being hot?

00:32:04.150 --> 00:32:05.832
IAN NI-LEWIS: Actually, what I'm
wondering is, how did she

00:32:05.832 --> 00:32:07.090
get the eyepatch?

00:32:07.090 --> 00:32:12.180
There she is in the act of
devoting her life to worship

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:13.550
and quiet contemplation.

00:32:13.550 --> 00:32:15.300
How did she lose an eye?

00:32:15.300 --> 00:32:17.830
DAN GALPIN: You know, that's one
of the great mysteries of

00:32:17.830 --> 00:32:18.700
this game, actually.

00:32:18.700 --> 00:32:20.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: I get the feeling
that the nuns in this

00:32:20.560 --> 00:32:22.700
game aren't real nuns.

00:32:22.700 --> 00:32:23.740
DAN GALPIN: It's
very possible.

00:32:23.740 --> 00:32:27.620
They also like to hang around
in bikinis apparently.

00:32:27.620 --> 00:32:33.060
So they're a new kind
of kick-butt nun.

00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:34.600
Actually, nuns are pretty
kick-butt, by the way, in

00:32:34.600 --> 00:32:37.450
general, just by
my experiences.

00:32:37.450 --> 00:32:39.285
Those are some serious
badass--

00:32:39.285 --> 00:32:39.540
IAN NI-LEWIS: Really?

00:32:39.540 --> 00:32:42.812
Did you meet a lot of nuns
in Hebrew school?

00:32:42.812 --> 00:32:45.160
DAN GALPIN: [LAUGH],
I actually did not

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:46.270
go to Hebrew school.

00:32:46.270 --> 00:32:47.730
But no--

00:32:47.730 --> 00:32:49.680
IAN NI-LEWIS: What kind
of a half-Jew are you?

00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:51.050
DAN GALPIN: Exactly.

00:32:51.050 --> 00:32:53.620
But I will say that--

00:32:53.620 --> 00:32:54.490
oh, here we are.

00:32:54.490 --> 00:32:56.660
So the problem with this game
for me, by the way, is that

00:32:56.660 --> 00:32:58.970
the game is actually well
thought out, but the controls

00:32:58.970 --> 00:33:02.480
for the games are actually
mostly what I'm fighting.

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:04.320
And the game tries to make
things easy for me.

00:33:04.320 --> 00:33:06.050
I say, I want to attack
that guy.

00:33:06.050 --> 00:33:09.070
And it continuously attacks.

00:33:09.070 --> 00:33:12.010
But I feel there's less visceral
pleasure in this.

00:33:12.010 --> 00:33:13.550
And it's still annoying.

00:33:13.550 --> 00:33:15.260
Because sometimes you're
dragging to say, I want to

00:33:15.260 --> 00:33:19.400
attack this guy, and you miss,
and the nun just walks over.

00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:23.100
IAN NI-LEWIS: Ooh, yeah,
that's rough.

00:33:23.100 --> 00:33:25.660
DAN GALPIN: Or that guy just
doesn't get attacked because

00:33:25.660 --> 00:33:26.450
he just happens to be
standing there.

00:33:26.450 --> 00:33:28.490
IAN NI-LEWIS: Hang on, though,
I think we need to--

00:33:28.490 --> 00:33:29.885
two, three, four, [SINGING]

00:33:29.885 --> 00:33:33.530
how do you solve a problem
like a skeleton?

00:33:33.530 --> 00:33:35.390
DAN GALPIN: So I can also--
there's also special abilities

00:33:35.390 --> 00:33:38.005
like I can make my nun
invisible there.

00:33:38.005 --> 00:33:40.610
So I can click on her, and
I can say, I want to go

00:33:40.610 --> 00:33:41.630
boom on this guy.

00:33:41.630 --> 00:33:43.530
Take out this gate.

00:33:43.530 --> 00:33:43.870
IAN NI-LEWIS: Gate?

00:33:43.870 --> 00:33:45.140
Is that what we're calling it?

00:33:45.140 --> 00:33:46.770
DAN GALPIN: It is the gate.

00:33:46.770 --> 00:33:48.190
It is, I believe, some
sort of hell-gate or

00:33:48.190 --> 00:33:48.980
something like that.

00:33:48.980 --> 00:33:51.300
IAN NI-LEWIS: Because that
resembles nothing

00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:53.020
so much as a gate.

00:33:53.020 --> 00:33:53.530
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:33:53.530 --> 00:33:58.480
So anyway, so that's
the basic game.

00:33:58.480 --> 00:34:01.100
The main issue with this game
that I had was that I kind of

00:34:01.100 --> 00:34:02.830
my found myself fighting
the controls.

00:34:02.830 --> 00:34:03.560
On the other hand--

00:34:03.560 --> 00:34:05.340
IAN NI-LEWIS: By the way, I
think we should pause and

00:34:05.340 --> 00:34:09.380
mention that our heads
are blocking a

00:34:09.380 --> 00:34:10.880
massive amount of gameplay.

00:34:10.880 --> 00:34:11.429
DAN GALPIN: That's true.

00:34:11.429 --> 00:34:14.030
IAN NI-LEWIS: Also,
don't care.

00:34:14.030 --> 00:34:14.739
It's our last show.

00:34:14.739 --> 00:34:16.830
Deal with it.

00:34:16.830 --> 00:34:18.100
Rock on.

00:34:18.100 --> 00:34:19.918
DAN GALPIN: Rock on.

00:34:19.918 --> 00:34:21.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:21.850 --> 00:34:25.639
DAN GALPIN: So Ian, before the
show, said, Dan, take this

00:34:25.639 --> 00:34:27.929
scene and sprinkle it liberally
throughout the show

00:34:27.929 --> 00:34:29.340
wherever it's appropriate.

00:34:29.340 --> 00:34:31.520
We're going to call this
the Dan awesome scene.

00:34:31.520 --> 00:34:32.290
And so there--

00:34:32.290 --> 00:34:34.679
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, Phamster
has done an amazing job.

00:34:34.679 --> 00:34:35.929
DAN GALPIN: As always.

00:34:39.170 --> 00:34:42.620
So the main issues with "Nun
Attack" that I saw is I kind

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:47.540
of wanted to feel a little bit
more feedback when I actually

00:34:47.540 --> 00:34:48.170
targeted someone.

00:34:48.170 --> 00:34:50.350
Like I wanted it to make it
clear this nun was targeting

00:34:50.350 --> 00:34:52.610
that character, and
I don't see that.

00:34:52.610 --> 00:34:54.300
And so there's lots of times
where the nun does something I

00:34:54.300 --> 00:34:55.239
don't expect.

00:34:55.239 --> 00:34:58.620
IAN NI-LEWIS: So yeah, you drag,
and it wasn't obvious

00:34:58.620 --> 00:35:00.940
when you could finish
your drag.

00:35:00.940 --> 00:35:01.610
DAN GALPIN: Exactly.

00:35:01.610 --> 00:35:02.080
And I really--

00:35:02.080 --> 00:35:02.750
IAN NI-LEWIS: But why?

00:35:02.750 --> 00:35:05.820
It seems like it would be so
obvious to just brighten that

00:35:05.820 --> 00:35:06.760
character up or something.

00:35:06.760 --> 00:35:09.460
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, and that's
what I think needs to happen.

00:35:09.460 --> 00:35:12.750
And also, once a character is
attacking someone, I want to

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:13.840
make it really obvious.

00:35:13.840 --> 00:35:16.640
Like I want a little picture
of the guy or a little

00:35:16.640 --> 00:35:19.450
direction, a little line
saying that this one is

00:35:19.450 --> 00:35:20.320
attacking that one.

00:35:20.320 --> 00:35:21.900
So there's a couple things I
think need to be done to make

00:35:21.900 --> 00:35:22.460
the game better.

00:35:22.460 --> 00:35:23.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know what I
think is a terrible idea?

00:35:23.740 --> 00:35:23.950
DAN GALPIN: What?

00:35:23.950 --> 00:35:25.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: Your picture
of a guy idea.

00:35:25.200 --> 00:35:26.180
I like mine better.

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:27.280
DAN GALPIN: OK.

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:30.220
And then "Nun Attack" also needs
to get rid of verifying

00:35:30.220 --> 00:35:31.350
the download every
time you launch,

00:35:31.350 --> 00:35:33.610
because that just sucks.

00:35:33.610 --> 00:35:33.820
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:35:33.820 --> 00:35:35.160
What is your dude doing?

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:36.960
I thought you were just--

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:39.645
are you actually doing a CRC
check on it or something?

00:35:39.645 --> 00:35:40.260
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:43.100
I wrote a little CRC checker.

00:35:43.100 --> 00:35:44.580
And so it unzips the
entire file.

00:35:44.580 --> 00:35:45.870
IAN NI-LEWIS: That was literally
just to pad your

00:35:45.870 --> 00:35:47.076
resume, wasn't it?

00:35:47.076 --> 00:35:51.810
It was like, 2012, wrote
a CRC check.

00:35:51.810 --> 00:35:53.700
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, that was
pretty much-- well, it was

00:35:53.700 --> 00:35:56.850
actually because when I was
developing it, I was making a

00:35:56.850 --> 00:35:58.860
download resume function.

00:35:58.860 --> 00:36:03.180
And when I made the download
resume function, I wanted to

00:36:03.180 --> 00:36:07.150
make sure that the
resumption--

00:36:07.150 --> 00:36:08.810
the downloads were actually
getting done correctly.

00:36:08.810 --> 00:36:10.735
So of course, the first thing
I did was wrote a verifier

00:36:10.735 --> 00:36:11.920
that would verify the CRCs.

00:36:11.920 --> 00:36:12.900
IAN NI-LEWIS: I love it.

00:36:12.900 --> 00:36:17.640
Dan wrote all of this over the
course of three months.

00:36:17.640 --> 00:36:22.050
Now that doesn't sound like much
except when you consider

00:36:22.050 --> 00:36:25.460
that we'd promised to have it
done in three weeks and not

00:36:25.460 --> 00:36:27.675
having it done delayed
the entire feature.

00:36:27.675 --> 00:36:30.100
DAN GALPIN: You know, you're
making me look bad here.

00:36:30.100 --> 00:36:32.410
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know what
makes you look great, though?

00:36:32.410 --> 00:36:33.660
DAN GALPIN: This hat.

00:36:38.010 --> 00:36:41.130
IAN NI-LEWIS: And if you don't
go mullet on us, I don't know

00:36:41.130 --> 00:36:42.680
what I'm gonna do.

00:36:42.680 --> 00:36:43.730
DAN GALPIN: Cancel the show.

00:36:43.730 --> 00:36:46.470
So let's--

00:36:46.470 --> 00:36:49.950
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, I'm telling
you, it's either mullet or--

00:36:49.950 --> 00:36:52.780
alternate possibility--

00:36:52.780 --> 00:36:54.800
shaved.

00:36:54.800 --> 00:36:55.170
DAN GALPIN: Shaved?

00:36:55.170 --> 00:36:56.310
IAN NI-LEWIS: That
would be awesome,

00:36:56.310 --> 00:36:57.480
especially with that beard.

00:36:57.480 --> 00:36:58.170
DAN GALPIN: Oh yeah.

00:36:58.170 --> 00:37:01.510
IAN NI-LEWIS: I'm thinking
Kane from "Command and

00:37:01.510 --> 00:37:02.430
Conquer."

00:37:02.430 --> 00:37:04.150
DAN GALPIN: Yes, yes.

00:37:04.150 --> 00:37:05.810
That would work.

00:37:05.810 --> 00:37:06.300
IAN NI-LEWIS: Let's face it.

00:37:06.300 --> 00:37:07.590
Everything Dan does is epic.

00:37:07.590 --> 00:37:09.330
DAN GALPIN: So this game was
actually one of the ones that

00:37:09.330 --> 00:37:11.550
was nominated, just in
case you thought I

00:37:11.550 --> 00:37:12.400
was going to ignore--

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:12.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, awesome.

00:37:12.670 --> 00:37:13.290
Who nominated it?

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:14.920
DAN GALPIN: I don't know.

00:37:14.920 --> 00:37:17.220
IAN NI-LEWIS: Let's call
him nominator guy.

00:37:17.220 --> 00:37:18.860
Nominator guy, let's
see how you did.

00:37:18.860 --> 00:37:20.720
DAN GALPIN: The developer of the
game-- so this is a game

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:23.050
which looks like another game
that we actually saw.

00:37:23.050 --> 00:37:23.870
Your goal is to get--

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:24.510
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh man.

00:37:24.510 --> 00:37:26.000
Is this a tilt game?

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.250
DAN GALPIN: It's a tilt game
where the goal is to get the--

00:37:28.250 --> 00:37:29.990
in fact, it's just like a game
that used to, I think, have

00:37:29.990 --> 00:37:31.110
sheep in it.

00:37:31.110 --> 00:37:32.440
But now it has ghosts in it.

00:37:32.440 --> 00:37:32.910
IAN NI-LEWIS: You
are kidding me.

00:37:32.910 --> 00:37:34.050
DAN GALPIN: It is
the same game.

00:37:34.050 --> 00:37:34.480
IAN NI-LEWIS: You
are kidding me.

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:34.800
DAN GALPIN: Nope.

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:37.120
IAN NI-LEWIS: OK, you know
what, nominator guy?

00:37:37.120 --> 00:37:39.620
I began to suspect that
you have an ulterior

00:37:39.620 --> 00:37:41.130
motive of some kind.

00:37:41.130 --> 00:37:44.240
DAN GALPIN: Well, I actually
like the burning ghosts rather

00:37:44.240 --> 00:37:46.040
than the sheep, honestly.

00:37:46.040 --> 00:37:46.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: I would
have gone with

00:37:46.670 --> 00:37:48.430
burning goats, but OK.

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:49.990
DAN GALPIN: Goats.

00:37:49.990 --> 00:37:51.710
Oh, and I've got to
avoid the fire.

00:37:51.710 --> 00:37:54.460
No, the fire, we bounce
off of the fire.

00:37:54.460 --> 00:37:56.600
IAN NI-LEWIS: I can't
see a thing here.

00:37:56.600 --> 00:37:58.580
It's all fire and--

00:37:58.580 --> 00:37:59.070
you know.

00:37:59.070 --> 00:38:01.200
It's got a sort of spotlight
thing going on.

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:02.250
DAN GALPIN: So cool--

00:38:02.250 --> 00:38:02.570
IAN NI-LEWIS: But
you know what?

00:38:02.570 --> 00:38:03.370
OK, can I just say this?

00:38:03.370 --> 00:38:05.010
DAN GALPIN: Box2D game,
yeah, yeah.

00:38:05.010 --> 00:38:06.148
IAN NI-LEWIS: Hang on.

00:38:06.148 --> 00:38:07.920
You think it's Box2d?

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:09.405
You think it's that complex?

00:38:09.405 --> 00:38:11.240
DAN GALPIN: It is Box2D because
it's using AndEngine.

00:38:11.240 --> 00:38:12.375
So I'm pretty sure it's Box2D.

00:38:12.375 --> 00:38:13.660
IAN NI-LEWIS: Eh, fair enough.

00:38:13.660 --> 00:38:14.980
No, but what I was--

00:38:14.980 --> 00:38:15.826
eh, go ahead.

00:38:15.826 --> 00:38:17.240
I don't care.

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:20.670
DAN GALPIN: So first of all,
this guy actually, what I will

00:38:20.670 --> 00:38:23.240
say, learned a lot from
professional game developers.

00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:24.410
Because professional
game developers do

00:38:24.410 --> 00:38:25.340
exactly this thing.

00:38:25.340 --> 00:38:28.450
They take a game that's
based on sheep, and

00:38:28.450 --> 00:38:30.460
they skin it for Halloween.

00:38:30.460 --> 00:38:32.230
And then they're like, look
at my game, everyone.

00:38:32.230 --> 00:38:34.460
I've got a Halloween game.

00:38:34.460 --> 00:38:36.990
Not that we know any developer
who would ever do

00:38:36.990 --> 00:38:38.230
something like that.

00:38:38.230 --> 00:38:38.510
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:38:38.510 --> 00:38:42.060
So when we say professional,
that's not necessarily a mark

00:38:42.060 --> 00:38:43.820
of quality.

00:38:43.820 --> 00:38:45.820
It just means they make money
from what they do.

00:38:45.820 --> 00:38:48.570
DAN GALPIN: Well, honestly,
if you can skin a game

00:38:48.570 --> 00:38:51.010
successfully, and actually, I
think this works better than

00:38:51.010 --> 00:38:52.470
the original sheep game.

00:38:52.470 --> 00:38:54.280
Because I never quite understood
why I was-- those

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:54.730
were sheep.

00:38:54.730 --> 00:38:56.150
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's a
really good point.

00:38:56.150 --> 00:38:57.355
Now the storyline is better.

00:38:57.355 --> 00:38:58.200
DAN GALPIN: It actually--

00:38:58.200 --> 00:38:59.170
IAN NI-LEWIS: Hang
on, hang on.

00:38:59.170 --> 00:39:03.020
I just got a message on
my Amp'd Mobile phone.

00:39:03.020 --> 00:39:05.050
Let's see.

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:05.350
DAN GALPIN: Hello.

00:39:05.350 --> 00:39:06.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh,
it's Googleween.

00:39:06.810 --> 00:39:11.380
DAN GALPIN: The Friday Games
Review has now become an ad

00:39:11.380 --> 00:39:13.010
for acceptable.tv.

00:39:13.010 --> 00:39:16.060
If you haven't seen
it, tune in.

00:39:16.060 --> 00:39:16.510
All right.

00:39:16.510 --> 00:39:22.940
So anyways, great job in
skinning your game.

00:39:22.940 --> 00:39:24.980
IAN NI-LEWIS: But
you know what?

00:39:24.980 --> 00:39:30.160
What a horrible job of skinning
your interactions.

00:39:30.160 --> 00:39:30.560
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:39:30.560 --> 00:39:32.460
IAN NI-LEWIS: How many dialogues
have we see now that

00:39:32.460 --> 00:39:33.790
have not been cool?

00:39:33.790 --> 00:39:34.370
DAN GALPIN: I know.

00:39:34.370 --> 00:39:35.400
And it's sad.

00:39:35.400 --> 00:39:37.480
IAN NI-LEWIS: And I know it's
our system dialogue.

00:39:37.480 --> 00:39:40.740
But I'm going to go out
on a limb here.

00:39:40.740 --> 00:39:42.270
Yeah, let's just come
out of the closet.

00:39:42.270 --> 00:39:44.830
Our system dialogues,
not cool.

00:39:44.830 --> 00:39:45.340
DAN GALPIN: Yeah,
don't use them.

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:48.030
Actually, as a general rule,
we tell developers, even in

00:39:48.030 --> 00:39:51.300
apps, not to use our system
dialogues for almost anything.

00:39:51.300 --> 00:39:55.480
Because the reality is, you
almost never want to stop the

00:39:55.480 --> 00:39:58.640
user's progress in the middle of
something unless it's sort

00:39:58.640 --> 00:40:02.050
of like, this action
will destroy all of

00:40:02.050 --> 00:40:03.200
your data, you know.

00:40:03.200 --> 00:40:05.650
Would you really, really
want to do this?

00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:07.490
Most of the time, if you're in
the middle of any kind of

00:40:07.490 --> 00:40:10.160
progression, what you'd want to
see is a separate screen.

00:40:10.160 --> 00:40:12.630
You'd want to see a true
interstitial screen rather

00:40:12.630 --> 00:40:14.650
than a dialogue, even
within apps.

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:16.880
Or you'd want to see it be a
part of the existing screen.

00:40:16.880 --> 00:40:21.190
In a game like this, what I want
to see is, take a look at

00:40:21.190 --> 00:40:24.790
what happened with a game like
"Angry Birds," where you

00:40:24.790 --> 00:40:27.360
actually see, yes, a dialogue.

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:29.050
But it's really an interstitial
screen.

00:40:29.050 --> 00:40:31.640
It feels very, very much
part of the game.

00:40:31.640 --> 00:40:33.350
And you get to see a whole
bunch of stats

00:40:33.350 --> 00:40:34.300
about how you did.

00:40:34.300 --> 00:40:36.380
And really, that would
be really nice.

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:38.400
I actually want to know how
many times did the ghost

00:40:38.400 --> 00:40:39.680
bounce off the wall.

00:40:39.680 --> 00:40:41.620
I want to know--

00:40:41.620 --> 00:40:43.250
I don't know, anything about
the game that might be

00:40:43.250 --> 00:40:43.710
interesting.

00:40:43.710 --> 00:40:44.990
IAN NI-LEWIS: Actually,
that's true.

00:40:44.990 --> 00:40:48.490
I always love stats.

00:40:48.490 --> 00:40:52.390
Definitely, as I've been playing
a game, I don't know

00:40:52.390 --> 00:40:54.815
if you've heard of it, little
bit of a new game for me,

00:40:54.815 --> 00:40:56.790
"Radiant Defense"--

00:40:56.790 --> 00:40:59.150
DAN GALPIN: You're playing
"Radiant Defense"?

00:40:59.150 --> 00:40:59.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:40:59.250 --> 00:41:00.560
DAN GALPIN: Holy moly.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:02.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: And I think to
myself, wow, it'd be really

00:41:02.670 --> 00:41:04.920
cool if I could get the
stats on this tower.

00:41:04.920 --> 00:41:05.850
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, absolutely.

00:41:05.850 --> 00:41:07.530
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, know
how much it's killed

00:41:07.530 --> 00:41:08.060
and stuff like that.

00:41:08.060 --> 00:41:08.740
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, I like that.

00:41:08.740 --> 00:41:10.150
That's a great idea.

00:41:10.150 --> 00:41:13.160
So that was "DemonBall,"
by the way, which

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:15.800
was actually nominated.

00:41:15.800 --> 00:41:19.100
I want to send props out to
"Greedy Spiders" for making

00:41:19.100 --> 00:41:19.620
those changes.

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:21.100
I'm not to going to go through
the game because we're running

00:41:21.100 --> 00:41:23.160
low on time.

00:41:23.160 --> 00:41:24.050
IAN NI-LEWIS: We are?

00:41:24.050 --> 00:41:24.960
DAN GALPIN: Relatively, yeah.

00:41:24.960 --> 00:41:27.820
So there's a non-Halloween
game I just want to call

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:30.730
attention to because it comes
from Clapfoot, and I

00:41:30.730 --> 00:41:31.930
absolutely really
love this game.

00:41:31.930 --> 00:41:32.842
IAN NI-LEWIS: Wait,
wait, wait.

00:41:32.842 --> 00:41:33.670
Who's Clapfoot again?

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:36.260
DAN GALPIN: Clapfoot
made "Tank Hero."

00:41:36.260 --> 00:41:36.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, OK.

00:41:36.720 --> 00:41:38.200
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, those guys.

00:41:38.200 --> 00:41:40.680
So this is their take--

00:41:40.680 --> 00:41:41.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's cool.

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:41.670
That's good-looking.

00:41:41.670 --> 00:41:43.140
DAN GALPIN: This is their
take on a shooting game.

00:41:43.140 --> 00:41:45.680
And this is pretty cool
for a freemium

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:47.030
shooting game, actually.

00:41:47.030 --> 00:41:48.390
They mostly nailed it.

00:41:48.390 --> 00:41:50.230
IAN NI-LEWIS: I totally like
that beginning scene.

00:41:50.230 --> 00:41:53.070
But now, what are we--

00:41:53.070 --> 00:41:56.120
we're basically looking at
a generic side-scroller?

00:41:56.120 --> 00:41:58.290
DAN GALPIN: Yes, it's a
generic side-scroller.

00:41:58.290 --> 00:42:00.000
IAN NI-LEWIS: But I like the
idea that they've got a

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:01.620
loadout screen and stuff.

00:42:01.620 --> 00:42:02.550
Can you actually--

00:42:02.550 --> 00:42:04.430
is there any kind of
RPG element to it?

00:42:04.430 --> 00:42:04.790
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:42:04.790 --> 00:42:07.670
So basically, you slowly
build up your ship.

00:42:07.670 --> 00:42:09.870
Or you can buy things to make
your ship more awesome.

00:42:09.870 --> 00:42:10.150
IAN NI-LEWIS: Nice.

00:42:10.150 --> 00:42:11.340
DAN GALPIN: And as you go
through the levels, there

00:42:11.340 --> 00:42:14.580
actually are four different
backgrounds in the game, and

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:17.770
you see them a lot, with lots
of different enemies that

00:42:17.770 --> 00:42:19.110
slowly start coming.

00:42:19.110 --> 00:42:19.620
Each level--

00:42:19.620 --> 00:42:20.780
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's the tough
thing about side-scrollers.

00:42:20.780 --> 00:42:22.100
You really need a lot of art.

00:42:22.100 --> 00:42:22.970
DAN GALPIN: You need
a lot of art.

00:42:22.970 --> 00:42:26.120
And so this game does not
have a lot of art.

00:42:26.120 --> 00:42:27.930
But it's actually really
fun on top of that.

00:42:27.930 --> 00:42:28.820
This is an hour--

00:42:28.820 --> 00:42:30.610
IAN NI-LEWIS: I have to mention,
because this just

00:42:30.610 --> 00:42:32.500
made me think of it,
so did you end

00:42:32.500 --> 00:42:34.950
up playing the "Zaxxon"?

00:42:34.950 --> 00:42:35.850
DAN GALPIN: I did not.

00:42:35.850 --> 00:42:37.220
IAN NI-LEWIS: Didn't they end up
calling it "Zaxxon Escape"?

00:42:37.220 --> 00:42:38.035
DAN GALPIN: It is, yeah.

00:42:38.035 --> 00:42:38.990
And it looks awesome.

00:42:38.990 --> 00:42:40.730
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know, I gotta
give a shoutout to these

00:42:40.730 --> 00:42:43.060
guys because they did some
interesting things.

00:42:43.060 --> 00:42:47.580
Now of course, I'm sorry, name
of the studio because I'm

00:42:47.580 --> 00:42:49.240
totally blanking on it.

00:42:49.240 --> 00:42:51.580
It's the same guys that did--

00:42:51.580 --> 00:42:52.620
DAN GALPIN: Free--

00:42:52.620 --> 00:42:53.620
IAN NI-LEWIS: "SnowboardX,"
right?

00:42:53.620 --> 00:42:54.450
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, what was it?

00:42:54.450 --> 00:42:54.790
IAN NI-LEWIS: FreeRange.

00:42:54.790 --> 00:42:55.130
DAN GALPIN: FreeRange.

00:42:55.130 --> 00:42:55.890
It was FreeRange.

00:42:55.890 --> 00:42:56.270
OK.

00:42:56.270 --> 00:42:56.640
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:42:56.640 --> 00:43:01.370
So FreeRange and our buddy
Wayne, Wayne Karo, your last

00:43:01.370 --> 00:43:03.260
name sounds like corn syrup.

00:43:03.260 --> 00:43:04.470
But anyway--

00:43:04.470 --> 00:43:05.800
DAN GALPIN: He's a sweet guy.

00:43:05.800 --> 00:43:08.400
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, no, awesome
guy, totally awesome.

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:11.000
I mean, the whole FreeRange
team, they've been in games

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:11.910
for a long, long time.

00:43:11.910 --> 00:43:12.280
DAN GALPIN: Absolutely.

00:43:12.280 --> 00:43:12.650
IAN NI-LEWIS: [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:12.650 --> 00:43:15.180
Tony Hawk, really cool stuff.

00:43:15.180 --> 00:43:16.620
The snowboard game is great.

00:43:16.620 --> 00:43:18.600
But anyway, so they put
out this thing.

00:43:18.600 --> 00:43:21.060
And obviously, it's interesting
because there's a

00:43:21.060 --> 00:43:24.750
lot of games that you could
say are inspired by other

00:43:24.750 --> 00:43:27.930
games, when what you really mean
is total ripoff of this

00:43:27.930 --> 00:43:29.390
other game.

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:34.590
"Zaxxon Escape" is inspired by
"Temple Run" in the most

00:43:34.590 --> 00:43:36.500
classic way, in that it is--

00:43:36.500 --> 00:43:37.560
DAN GALPIN: It's true
inspiration.

00:43:37.560 --> 00:43:40.540
The game is heavily,
heavily different.

00:43:40.540 --> 00:43:40.900
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:43:40.900 --> 00:43:43.970
And it adds a third dimension.

00:43:43.970 --> 00:43:47.100
It's like "Temple Run"
meets "Descent."

00:43:47.100 --> 00:43:48.050
So really cool stuff.

00:43:48.050 --> 00:43:49.990
And they originally
showed it to us.

00:43:49.990 --> 00:43:51.180
I think it was a
different name.

00:43:51.180 --> 00:43:53.140
And then they hooked up and Sega
and they got the "Zaxxon"

00:43:53.140 --> 00:43:53.770
name on it, which--

00:43:53.770 --> 00:43:54.195
DAN GALPIN: Shh!

00:43:54.195 --> 00:43:55.180
IAN NI-LEWIS: --was
absolutely cool.

00:43:55.180 --> 00:43:56.300
DAN GALPIN: It was designed
as Zaxxon.

00:43:56.300 --> 00:43:56.640
Shh.

00:43:56.640 --> 00:43:59.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: It was,
absolutely.

00:43:59.320 --> 00:44:00.150
Which I love.

00:44:00.150 --> 00:44:02.675
I'm glad that they brought
that name back.

00:44:02.675 --> 00:44:03.910
That is some cool stuff.

00:44:03.910 --> 00:44:06.870
DAN GALPIN: So "Zaxxon," I can
tell you, many years ago, I

00:44:06.870 --> 00:44:08.700
actually owned a "Zaxxon"
stand-up.

00:44:11.330 --> 00:44:11.850
IAN NI-LEWIS: Wow.

00:44:11.850 --> 00:44:12.890
DAN GALPIN: I know, I know.

00:44:12.890 --> 00:44:15.880
IAN NI-LEWIS: You're like
that kid in that one

00:44:15.880 --> 00:44:17.130
Richard Pryor movie.

00:44:17.130 --> 00:44:18.630
You have everything.

00:44:18.630 --> 00:44:19.070
DAN GALPIN: No.

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:23.120
But I did have a "Zaxxon"
stand-up, back when they came

00:44:23.120 --> 00:44:23.750
down in price.

00:44:23.750 --> 00:44:27.030
You can get them
for about $300.

00:44:27.030 --> 00:44:29.570
IAN NI-LEWIS: He means $3,000.

00:44:29.570 --> 00:44:30.080
DAN GALPIN: Thank you.

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:30.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know why?

00:44:30.250 --> 00:44:31.770
DAN GALPIN: Thank you, thank
you, translator man.

00:44:31.770 --> 00:44:33.010
IAN NI-LEWIS: Dan is
phenomenally wealthy.

00:44:33.010 --> 00:44:34.315
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, right.

00:44:34.315 --> 00:44:35.950
IAN NI-LEWIS: Come on--

00:44:35.950 --> 00:44:37.960
houses, exactly, and a Prius.

00:44:37.960 --> 00:44:40.435
DAN GALPIN: Hey, all I can say
is that you drive a BMW.

00:44:40.435 --> 00:44:43.970
IAN NI-LEWIS: How did you
get a Prius, anyway?

00:44:43.970 --> 00:44:49.790
BMWs, in San Jose, Silicon
Valley, dude, you find those

00:44:49.790 --> 00:44:52.820
like on the side of
the road, man.

00:44:52.820 --> 00:44:56.140
DAN GALPIN: Well, certainly once
their lease has run out.

00:44:56.140 --> 00:44:59.950
But yeah, no, this
is a lot of fun.

00:44:59.950 --> 00:45:01.150
You can waste a lot of
time with this game.

00:45:01.150 --> 00:45:02.190
And honestly, they did
a really, really

00:45:02.190 --> 00:45:02.940
great job with it.

00:45:02.940 --> 00:45:07.030
So good use of Android,
and I've been

00:45:07.030 --> 00:45:08.150
really happy with it.

00:45:08.150 --> 00:45:09.240
IAN NI-LEWIS: Cool, cool.

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:09.910
DAN GALPIN: I wanted
to give a shoutout.

00:45:09.910 --> 00:45:13.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now I have to ask,
though, is that really

00:45:13.200 --> 00:45:15.230
full resolution?

00:45:15.230 --> 00:45:18.180
DAN GALPIN: That is, as far as
I can tell, full resolution.

00:45:18.180 --> 00:45:22.180
It's just that the artwork in
the back, the textures are a

00:45:22.180 --> 00:45:22.750
little blurry.

00:45:22.750 --> 00:45:24.040
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's
just the beer.

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:25.220
DAN GALPIN: No, the textures
are blurry.

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:27.280
You can see if you look at the
sharp lines around the

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:29.595
geometry, you can see that's
actually full resolution.

00:45:29.595 --> 00:45:30.420
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah,
I saw that.

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:32.030
So it's really just
the backgrounds.

00:45:32.030 --> 00:45:32.740
DAN GALPIN: Yeah.

00:45:32.740 --> 00:45:34.410
IAN NI-LEWIS: So I guess
we're saying that's a

00:45:34.410 --> 00:45:35.650
depth of field effect?

00:45:35.650 --> 00:45:39.780
DAN GALPIN: No, it's just
low-resolution textures.

00:45:39.780 --> 00:45:41.045
IAN NI-LEWIS: This screen,
though, is really cool.

00:45:41.045 --> 00:45:41.840
I like this screen.

00:45:41.840 --> 00:45:42.850
DAN GALPIN: Yeah, yeah.

00:45:42.850 --> 00:45:43.930
That screen is awesome.

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:45.590
It makes you think the game is
going to be perhaps a little

00:45:45.590 --> 00:45:47.570
more epic than it actually is.

00:45:47.570 --> 00:45:49.250
But I really love the game.

00:45:49.250 --> 00:45:50.540
I thought they did a beautiful
